      <p><strong>Skip the loading phase.</strong> The traditional 20g/day for 5-7 days loading protocol was designed for male bodybuilders trying to saturate muscles quickly. For women starting creatine for general health, strength, or cognitive benefits, taking 3-5g daily reaches full muscle saturation in 3-4 weeks without the bloating, GI discomfort, or wasted product associated with loading. Patient consistency outperforms aggressive loading every time.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SAFETY -->
    <h2>Is Creatine Safe for Women? The 500-Study Evidence Base</h2>

    <p>Creatine monohydrate is one of the most extensively studied supplements in nutritional science. The safety database includes <strong>over 500 peer-reviewed studies</strong> spanning short-term high-dose use (up to 30g/day for several days), long-term moderate dose use (3-5g/day for up to 5 years), and special populations including pregnant women, older adults, and individuals with kidney concerns.</p>

    <p>The consensus across this evidence base is unambiguous: creatine is safe at recommended doses in healthy adults of both sexes. A 2021 review in the <em>British Journal of Sports Medicine</em> specifically examined creatine in female participants and found no adverse effects on kidney function, liver function, hormonal balance, menstrual cycle regularity, or fertility. Women with pre-existing kidney disease should consult a healthcare provider before starting, but for healthy women, the safety margin is extremely large.</p>

    <p>For a comprehensive look at potential side effects and how to minimize them, see our companion article on <a href="/blog/creatine-side-effects-in-women/">creatine side effects in women</a>. For pregnancy-specific guidance, see <a href="/blog/creatine-while-pregnant/">creatine while pregnant</a>.</p>

    <!-- WHO BENEFITS MOST -->
    <h2>Which Women Benefit Most from Creatine?</h2>

    <div class="info-cards">
