        <p>The performance and recovery benefits are most visible in this demographic. Strength gains, faster recovery between training sessions, improved high-intensity output, and better cognitive performance under work and life stress.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="user" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Women in Perimenopause (35-50)</h3>
        <p>Hormonal changes accelerate muscle loss and reduce energy. Creatine helps preserve lean mass, supports cognition through brain fog episodes, and complements resistance training for body composition maintenance.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="user" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Postmenopausal Women</h3>
        <p>Possibly the demographic that benefits most. Creatine supports bone mineral density (critical when osteoporosis risk accelerates), preserves lean muscle, and contributes to mood and cognitive resilience during a phase of significant biological transition.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <div class="info-card-ico"><Icon name="user" size={22} /></div>
        <h3>Vegetarian and Vegan Women</h3>
        <p>Dietary creatine comes almost exclusively from meat and fish, meaning vegetarian and vegan women have lower baseline creatine stores. Supplementation produces particularly strong effects because they are starting from a deficit.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

